  "prompt": "How does insertWithOnConflict() work in SQLite? ",
  "response": "In SQLite, `insertWithOnConflict()` is a method used to insert a row into a table with specific conflict resolution strategies. Here's a comprehensive explanation:\n\n```java\n// Basic syntax\ndatabase.insertWithOnConflict(String table, \n                               String nullColumnHack, \n                               ContentValues values, \n                               int conflictAlgorithm)\n```\n\nKey Parameters:\n1. `table`: Name of the table to insert into\n2. `nullColumnHack`: Allows inserting an empty row if values are empty\n3. `values`: ContentValues object with column names and values\n4. `conflictAlgorithm`: How to handle conflicts\n\nConflict Resolution Strategies:\n```java\n// SQLiteDatabase conflict resolution constants\nCONFLICT_REPLACE    // Replace existing row\nCONFLICT_IGNORE     // Skip insert if conflict occurs\nCONFLICT_ABORT      // Abort the transaction (default behavior)\nCONFLICT_FAIL       // Fail the entire operation\nCONFLICT_ROLLBACK   // Rollback the transaction\n```\n\nExample Usage:\n```java\n// Insert or replace existing row\nlong rowId = database.insertWithOnConflict(\n    \"users\", \n    null, \n    contentValues, \n    SQLiteDatabase.CONFLICT_REPLACE\n);\n\n// Insert only if row doesn't already exist\nlong rowId = database.insertWithOnConflict(\n    \"users\", \n    null, \n    contentValues, \n    SQLiteDatabase.CONFLICT_IGNORE\n);\n```\n\nCommon Scenarios:\n1. Unique Constraint Handling\n```java\n// When you have a unique column and want to replace existing\ndatabase.insertWithOnConflict(\n    \"users\", \n    null, \n    values, \n    SQLiteDatabase.CONFLICT_REPLACE\n);\n```\n\n2. Avoiding Duplicate Entries\n```java\n// Silently skip if entry already exists\ndatabase.insertWithOnConflict(\n    \"users\", \n    null, \n    values, \n    SQLiteDatabase.CONFLICT_IGNORE\n);\n```\n\nReturn Value:\n- Returns the row ID of the inserted row\n- Returns -1 if insertion fails\n\nBest Practices:\n- Use appropriate conflict resolution strategy\n- Handle potential exceptions\n- Check return value for successful insertion\n\nComprehensive Example:\n```java\ntry {\n    ContentValues values = new ContentValues();\n    values.put(\"username\", \"johndoe\");\n    values.put(\"email\", \"john@example.com\");\n\n    long rowId = database.insertWithOnConflict(\n        \"users\", \n        null, \n        values, \n        SQLiteDatabase.CONFLICT_REPLACE\n    );\n\n    if (rowId != -1) {\n        // Successful insertion or replacement\n        Log.d(\"Database\", \"Row inserted/replaced: \" + rowId);\n    }\n} catch (SQLException e) {\n    Log.e(\"Database\", \"Insertion error\", e);\n}\n```\n\nPerformance Considerations:\n- `CONFLICT_REPLACE` can be slower for large datasets\n- Choose conflict strategy based on specific use case\n- Consider unique indexes for optimal performance\n\nKey Differences from Regular `insert()`:\n- More granular conflict resolution\n- More control over how duplicate entries are handled\n- Allows custom handling of constraint violations\n\nBy understanding and properly using `insertWithOnConflict()`, you can create more robust database interactions with precise control over insertion behavior.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
